00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:43.520
&gt;&gt; I was shocked.

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:44.940
I didn't think we'd find much.

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:49.200
And we found emissions
off the freaking charts.

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:54.760
&gt;&gt; We found that many of the
samples exceeded those standards.

00:12:54.760 --> 00:13:00.200 position:56%
Some for benzene were something like
10,000 times above the standard.

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:02.980
&gt;&gt; Many of the toxic chemicals
that are known to cause cancer

00:13:02.980 --> 00:13:07.030
that we found in this report
were, in some cases, hundreds.

00:13:07.030 --> 00:13:08.510
In other cases, thousands.

00:13:08.510 --> 00:13:13.290
And in one case, 22 million
times over the EPA cancer risk.

00:13:13.290 --> 00:13:15.930
&gt;&gt; These are enormous releases.

00:13:15.930 --> 00:13:18.800
Many of these components
are neurotoxins.

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:21.520
At high concentrations, they
can actually cause coma.

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:27.070
But at later concentrations, they
tend to reduce brain function.

00:13:27.070 --> 00:13:30.550
The long-term effects,
the biggest one is cancer.

00:13:30.550 --> 00:13:33.430
Because several of these
are known human carcinogens.

00:13:33.430 --> 00:13:38.010
&gt;&gt; So when we started doing
the Bucket Brigade, this five,

00:13:38.010 --> 00:13:40.950
six state Bucket Brigade,
we didn't intend

00:13:40.950 --> 00:13:43.430
on doing the peer-reviewed article.

00:13:43.430 --> 00:13:45.560 position:56%
We were just going to do the report.

00:13:45.560 --> 00:13:49.830
&gt;&gt; I became involved in the
fracking study when the groups

00:13:49.830 --> 00:13:54.190
that had coordinated the
community-based activities

00:13:54.190 --> 00:13:58.390
approached me for assistance
doing the statistical analysis

00:13:58.390 --> 00:14:01.580
of the data, writing
up the publication,

00:14:01.580 --> 00:14:04.340
and getting it published
in a peer-reviewed journal.

00:14:04.340 --> 00:14:07.560
And whenever there is
this kind of study,

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:10.150
having a peer-reviewed
publication is sort

00:14:10.150 --> 00:14:16.240
of the good housekeeping seal
of legitimacy of a study.

00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:20.310
&gt;&gt; What happens with citizen
science is everybody disses it.

00:14:20.310 --> 00:14:23.330
So the peer-reviewed article
was extremely important

00:14:23.330 --> 00:14:27.260
because it gave validity
to citizen science.

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:30.450
&gt;&gt; I think that's why we
got taken so seriously,

00:14:30.450 --> 00:14:33.990
that our journal article
had been published,

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:37.250
and this is what academic
scientists and doctors were saying

00:14:37.250 --> 00:14:40.060
about the extreme hazard
from oil and gas development.

00:14:40.060 --> 00:14:43.220
And there was widespread
coverage across the U.S.

00:14:43.220 --> 00:14:46.970
and actually globally of both the
peer-reviewed study and the report.

00:14:46.970 --> 00:14:48.830
And it had a major impact.

00:14:48.830 --> 00:14:50.800
&gt;&gt; I think the greatest influence

00:14:50.800 --> 00:14:56.070
from the warning signs report
was for the ban in New York.

00:14:56.070 --> 00:15:00.190
&gt;&gt; Our fracking study was waved
by the commissioner of health

00:15:00.190 --> 00:15:03.730
when he made the announcement
that the governor

00:15:03.730 --> 00:15:07.010
of New York was banning fracking.

00:15:09.120 --> 00:15:12.690
&gt;&gt; Geoff Haines-Stiles: So the last
genre of citizen science I'm going

00:15:12.690 --> 00:15:14.810
to talk about is really
more like crowd sourcing.

00:15:14.810 --> 00:15:17.880
And this is where there's so much
data, rather than the lack of data

00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:19.180
in the case of fracking

00:15:19.180 --> 00:15:24.650
or the public lab work,
the Deepwater Horizon.

00:15:24.650 --> 00:15:26.840
There is so much data
coming out of research lab

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:30.250
that you can crowd source it much
faster than the work could be done

00:15:30.250 --> 00:15:31.690
by researchers themselves.

00:15:31.690 --> 00:15:36.850
So this story is about the folks up
at Cornell who are looking to see

00:15:36.850 --> 00:15:39.610
if they can figure out
the causes of Alzheimer's.

00:15:39.610 --> 00:15:42.030
And they think it's reduced
blood flow in the brain.

00:15:42.030 --> 00:15:43.700
They experiment on mice.

00:15:43.700 --> 00:15:45.830
They take videos of mouse brains.

00:15:45.830 --> 00:15:48.650
And they then have the problem
that it takes them a week

00:15:48.650 --> 00:15:51.030
to capture the data, but
a year to analyze it.

00:15:51.030 --> 00:15:52.590
So they've turned to the crowd.

00:15:52.590 --> 00:15:55.130
They've borrowed from
or adapted examples

00:15:55.130 --> 00:15:58.460
from successful gamified
citizen science projects,

00:15:58.460 --> 00:16:00.920 position:56%
including the NASA Stardust Mission,

00:16:00.920 --> 00:16:06.170 position:56%
where 30,000 people playing a game
were essentially able to find traces

00:16:06.170 --> 00:16:09.910
of interstellar particles,
and EyeWire,

00:16:09.910 --> 00:16:12.540
which is looking at
neurons in the brain.

00:16:12.540 --> 00:16:16.660
Putting this together, they
were able to borrow from all

00:16:16.660 --> 00:16:21.710
of the lessons of web games in
terms of having leader boards,

00:16:21.710 --> 00:16:24.280
competition, fighting to
have your name up there

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:25.770
on the top of the leader board.

00:16:25.770 --> 00:16:29.380
And this is how a citizen
science project was demoed

00:16:29.380 --> 00:16:33.490 position:56%
in a retirement community in Florida
playing the store catcher's game.

00:16:33.490 --> 00:16:36.230
You can see the excitement
that these senior citizens got

00:16:36.230 --> 00:16:39.510
from trying to help speed
up Alzheimer's research.

00:16:39.510 --> 00:16:43.240
[ Music ]

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:48.440
&gt;&gt; In late 2016, EyesOnALZ released
its Stall Catchers game based

00:16:48.440 --> 00:16:50.540
on the Stardust Interface.

00:16:50.540 --> 00:16:53.770
The public was invited to
help crowd source the analysis

00:16:53.770 --> 00:16:56.100
of blocked blood vessels.

00:16:56.100 --> 00:16:59.690
Some of the first players
were in Central Florida.

00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:02.500
They were retirees who had
chosen the warm climate

00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:05.430
in a community with plenty to do.

00:17:06.470 --> 00:17:11.180
&gt;&gt; How many of you have family,
friends, somebody close to you

00:17:11.180 --> 00:17:16.410
that either has or did have
Alzheimer's, or you have it?

00:17:16.410 --> 00:17:18.220
Just about everybody, huh?

00:17:18.220 --> 00:17:23.710
If only the scientists work on it,
it might take as much as 30 years.

00:17:23.710 --> 00:17:27.440
And for most of us, that's
not going be a big benefit.

00:17:27.440 --> 00:17:29.730
This is what the game looks like.

00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:34.020
And you can get it on your
phone, your tablet, your laptop.

00:17:34.020 --> 00:17:35.320
&gt;&gt; Does the game change every day?

00:17:35.320 --> 00:17:37.210
&gt;&gt; Yes, yes, they keep going.

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:39.550
They keep putting you through.

00:17:39.550 --> 00:17:40.850
&gt;&gt; What do you think?

00:17:40.850 --> 00:17:42.150
&gt;&gt; Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:17:42.150 --> 00:17:47.180 position:56%
&gt;&gt; How many think that it's flowing?

00:17:47.180 --> 00:17:52.680
How many think it's stalled?

00:17:52.680 --> 00:17:54.010
Shall we find out?

00:17:54.010 --> 00:17:55.310
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:17:55.310 --> 00:17:57.300
&gt;&gt; Well, try Stall then, okay?

00:17:57.300 --> 00:18:04.340
I've got 402 points.

00:18:04.340 --> 00:18:06.680
Thank you very much.

00:18:06.680 --> 00:18:07.980
There we go.

00:18:07.980 --> 00:18:09.280
We're climbing.

00:18:09.280 --> 00:18:10.580
We're climbing.

00:18:10.580 --> 00:18:11.880
Every time we find a stalled one

00:18:11.880 --> 00:18:13.210
that is really stalled,
we are helping big time.

00:18:13.210 --> 00:18:15.970
&gt;&gt; One of the things that I
like about this research is

00:18:15.970 --> 00:18:20.820
that we can help my mother's
generation, but I'm 64.

00:18:20.820 --> 00:18:23.730
And, you know, while
I want to help my mom,

00:18:23.730 --> 00:18:27.550
this is going to help,
I call kids, my age.

00:18:28.730 --> 00:18:32.900
&gt;&gt; EyesOnALZ will keep on
refining its game play interface.

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:36.550
But its greatest impact on
Alzheimer's research will come

00:18:36.550 --> 00:18:39.860
from the limitless
power of the crowd.

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:46.140
&gt;&gt; Geoff Haines-Stiles: So
one of the common questions

00:18:46.140 --> 00:18:50.210
about citizen science is the
data quality reliable enough?

00:18:50.210 --> 00:18:53.980
And the folks behind the
EyesOnALZ project worked on that,

00:18:53.980 --> 00:18:56.240
and they have been able
to find that relative

00:18:56.240 --> 00:19:01.250
to laboratory grade research,
the crowd is doing very well.

00:19:01.250 --> 00:19:03.270
Originally, they thought they
would have to have 20 members

00:19:03.270 --> 00:19:05.620
of the crowd to validate
each result.

00:19:05.620 --> 00:19:09.440
They've now gone down to 7 to
8 people, looking at each piece

00:19:09.440 --> 00:19:12.030
of data to get quality results.

00:19:12.030 --> 00:19:15.660
So data quality is often
raised about citizen science.

00:19:15.660 --> 00:19:19.970
The quality of many citizen science
projects has been demonstrated

00:19:19.970 --> 00:19:23.400
in statistics that I think any
of you would find convincing.

00:19:23.400 --> 00:19:26.160
While our series was on the
air back in April and May

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:30.310 position:56%
and PBS stations will be rerunning
it on into the next couple of years,

00:19:30.310 --> 00:19:33.210
but just last weekend, we
did a global catch-a-thon,

00:19:33.210 --> 00:19:36.240
modeled on the sort of
open street map map-a-thons

00:19:36.240 --> 00:19:38.810
in which you give people
pizza, have them get together

00:19:38.810 --> 00:19:40.970
to do a mapping of streets.

00:19:40.970 --> 00:19:44.390
This time, EyesOnALZ
coordinated a global effort,

00:19:44.390 --> 00:19:47.080
22 teams in 6 different continents

00:19:47.080 --> 00:19:51.130
on 6 different continents playing
a game within an hour to see

00:19:51.130 --> 00:19:55.560
who could actually code the
largest number of stalls.

00:19:55.560 --> 00:19:57.090
And you can see some
of the people there.

00:19:57.090 --> 00:20:03.120
Guatemala, El Salvador,
Chile, China, Brazil,

00:20:03.120 --> 00:20:05.430
all around the world people
were online playing this game

00:20:05.430 --> 00:20:08.900
when we did a live zoom
hangout to document that.

00:20:08.900 --> 00:20:11.000
The winners were actually
done in Chile.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:16.470
You can see that they annotated
1,955 examples of brain science,

00:20:16.470 --> 00:20:20.510
and then they celebrated and
everybody got to share in that.

00:20:20.510 --> 00:20:23.670
Citizen science has, in fact,
become a global phenomenon

00:20:23.670 --> 00:20:26.410
with citizen science
associations in Australia,

00:20:26.410 --> 00:20:30.460
and also in Europe
being very strong.

00:20:30.460 --> 00:20:34.410
Some of the apps developed in Spain
are actually now being used here

00:20:34.410 --> 00:20:35.810
in the United States as well.

00:20:35.810 --> 00:20:40.470
This is called mosquito alert
with the concern about Zika.

00:20:40.470 --> 00:20:43.360
Anything that citizens
can do to report the areas

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:51.120
in which there is a breeding site
for mosquitoes is very important.

00:20:51.120 --> 00:20:53.920
This little video just shows
you that these are the sites

00:20:53.920 --> 00:20:57.270
of traditional locations
of live traps.

00:20:57.270 --> 00:20:59.810
But they're fairly limited.

00:20:59.810 --> 00:21:02.070
This is the number of
citizen science reports

00:21:02.070 --> 00:21:04.230
that came in in Spain.

